Question 1 (15 points): Line Chart

#import data
GDP_data <- read_csv("E:/SIT/EM622/HW/Midterm/GDP_data.csv")

#gather gdp from 2006 to 2015 into one column
gather_gdp <- GDP_data %>%
  select(-c(3:10)) %>%
  gather(key = 'year', value = 'gdp', Y2006, Y2007, Y2008, Y2009, Y2010, Y2011, Y2012, Y2013, Y2014, Y2015)

#split top 4 countries and others
gdp_top4 <- gather_gdp %>%
  filter(Country == 'United States' | Country == 'China'| Country == 'Japan' | Country == 'Germany')
gdp_other <- anti_join(gather_gdp, gdp_top4, by = "Country")

#plot top 4 countries
a <- ggplot(gdp_top4, aes(x = year, y = gdp, color = Country, group = Country)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.5) + geom_point(size = 3.5) + scale_colour_manual(values=c('China'="darkorange2", 'United States'="mediumorchid3", 'Germany'="darkolivegreen4",'Japan'="cadetblue3"))

#plot other countries
a <- a + geom_line(data = gdp_other, mapping = aes(x = factor(year), y = gdp), color = 'grey80', size = 1.5) + 
  geom_point(data = gdp_other, color = 'grey80', size = 3.5) 

#edit theme and scale
a <- a + scale_x_discrete(name = 'Year', labels = c('2006','','','2009','','','2012','','', '2015')) + 
  scale_y_continuous(name = 'GDP(USD in trillions)', breaks = c(0,5e+12, 10e+12, 15e+12), labels = c('0', '5', '10', '15')) + ggtitle('Top 4 Countries in GDP form 2006 to 2015' )
a <- a +theme_bw() + theme(plot.title = element_text(size=18, face="bold"),
                              axis.text=element_text(size=12, color = 'black'), 
                              axis.title=element_text(size=14,face="bold"), legend.position="none")

#add annotations
a <- a + annotate("text", label = "United States", x = 6.5, y = 16.38e+12, size = 6, angle = 16.7, colour = "mediumorchid3") +
  annotate("text", label = "China", x = 6.5, y = 8.52e+12, size = 6, angle = 20, colour = "darkorange2") +
  annotate("text", label = "Japan", x = 6.5, y = 6.68e+12, size = 6, angle = 1, colour = "cadetblue3") +
  annotate("text", label = "Germany", x = 6.5, y = 4.16e+12, size = 6, angle = -4, colour = "darkolivegreen4") +
  annotate("text", label = "Others", x = 6.5, y = 3.2e+12, size = 6, angle = -2, colour = "grey80")
  
a

Question 2 (15 points): Outlay Treemap

#import data
outlays <- read_csv("E:/SIT/EM622/HW/Midterm/outlays.csv")

#clean data
clean_outlays <- outlays %>%
  select(c('Agency.Name', 'Bureau.Name', 'X2017')) %>%
  filter(X2017 > 7500000)  %>%
  group_by(Agency.Name, Bureau.Name) %>%
  summarise(X2017 = sum(X2017)) %>%
  arrange(desc(X2017))

#treemap
library(treemap)
treemap(dtf = clean_outlays, index = c('Agency.Name', 'Bureau.Name'),
        vSize = 'X2017', vColor = 'X2017', type = 'index', title = 'Obama 2017 Budget Outlays',
        palette = 'Set2', 
        fontsize.title = 20,
        fontsize.labels=c(15,12), 
        fontface.labels=c(2,1),                  
        bg.labels=c("transparent"),              
        align.labels= list(
          c("center", "center"), 
          c("right", "bottom")
        ),                                 
        overlap.labels=0.5)

Question 3 (15 points): Story about healthcare related outlays

#Clean data
health_outlays <- outlays %>%
  filter(Agency.Name == 'Department of Health and Human Services') %>%
  select(c(9,13:73)) %>%
  group_by(Subfunction.Title) %>%
  gather(key = 'Year', value = 'Budget',2:62) %>%
  filter(Budget > 0, Year != 'TQ') %>%
  group_by(Year, Subfunction.Title) %>%
  summarise(sum_Budget = sum(Budget)) %>%
  mutate(per=sum_Budget/sum(sum_Budget))

#choose the top 8 aspects
health_outlays_top8 <- health_outlays%>%
  group_by(Subfunction.Title)%>%
  summarise(sum_Budget = sum(sum_Budget)) %>%
  mutate(per=sum_Budget/sum(sum_Budget)) %>%
  arrange(desc(sum_Budget)) %>%
  head(8)

health_outlays <- health_outlays %>%
  filter(Subfunction.Title %in% health_outlays_top8$Subfunction.Title)

#plot the base graph
c <- ggplot(health_outlays, aes(x = Year, y = per, fill = Subfunction.Title)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) + coord_flip() + scale_fill_brewer(palette = 'Set2')

#edit the scale and theme
c <- c +scale_x_discrete(breaks = c('X1965', 'X1975', 'X1985', 'X1995', 'X2005', 'X2015'), labels = c(1965,1975,1985,1995,2005,2015))+
  scale_y_continuous(name = 'Percentage', breaks = c(0,0.25,0.5,0.75,1), labels=c('0', '25%', '50%', '75%', '100%')) 
c <- c + theme_minimal() + ggtitle('Where has the healthcare budget been used?') + 
  labs(fill='Function') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=20, face="bold"),
                                 axis.text=element_text(size=12, color = 'black'), 
                                 axis.title=element_text(size=14,face="bold"), 
        legend.position="bottom", legend.text=element_text(size=12), legend.title=element_text(size=14))

#add annotation
c <- c + annotate("text", label = "Other income security\n1.3 billion", x = 5, y = 0.17, size = 5.7,  colour = "darkorange2") +
  annotate("text", label = "Medicare\n20.1 billion", x = 36, y = 0.41, size = 6,  colour = "green4") +
  annotate("text", label = "Health care services\n8 billion", x = 40, y = 0.87, size = 6,  colour = "slateblue4")

Question 4 (15 points): Heatmap

library(d3heatmap)
energy_data <- read_csv("E:/SIT/EM622/HW/Midterm/energy_data.csv")
energy_data <- as.data.frame(energy_data)
energy_data[is.na(energy_data)] <- 0
d3heatmap(energy_data[,3:7], scale = "row", 
         annColors = "Pastel1", labRow = energy_data$Country, 
         cellwidth = 150, cellheight = 20, fontsize = 10)

Explain: From the Column Dendrograms, five different energy fuels are categorized into three groups: electricity and heat as one group, gases and liquids as another, and solids energy is alone. In one certain group, each country get close points of different energy fuels. Seen from the colour change of each columns, we could fuzzyly analyze that, those countries, who rely most on gases or liquids fuel, are shortage in solids fuel. In addition, no more countries make efforts on electricity or heat, maybe because it has run out for tens of years endless using, or maybe its not enviromental.

Question 5 (15 points): Multivariate Plot

library(chorddiag)
library(RColorBrewer)
energy.mat <- as.matrix(energy_data[, 3:7], ncol = 5)

rownames(energy.mat) <- energy_data$Country
dimnames(energy.mat ) <- list(Country = energy_data$Country,
                               Energy = c('Solids','Liquids','Gases','Electricity','Heat'))

mycolors <- c(brewer.pal(n = 8, name = "Set2"))
chorddiag(energy.mat, groupColors = mycolors,type = "bipartite", groupnamePadding = 45, groupnameFontsize = 19,
          tickInterval = 5000, categorynamePadding=135)

Question 6 (15 points): Geographic Map

library(maps)
library(mapproj)
#import data
map_df <- read_csv("E:/SIT/EM622/HW/Midterm/map_df.csv")
mapdata <- map_data('world')

theme_clean <- function(base_size = 12) {
  require(grid) # Needed for unit() function
  theme_grey(base_size) %+replace%theme(
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks.length = unit(0, "cm"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(margin=unit(0, "cm")),
    axis.text.y = element_text(margin=unit(0, "cm")),
    panel.margin = unit(0, "lines"),
    plot.margin = unit(c(0, 0, 0, 0), "lines"),
    complete = TRUE
  )}

#data clean
setdiff(map_df$Country_Area, mapdata$region)
## [1] "Brunei Darussalam"    "Hong Kong"            "Russian Federation"  
## [4] "Syrian Arab Republic" "Trinidad and Tobago"  "United Kingdom"      
## [7] "United States"
map_df$Country_Area[map_df$Country_Area == 'Russian Federation'] <- 'Russia'
map_df$Country_Area[map_df$Country_Area == 'United Kingdom'] <- 'UK'
map_df$Country_Area[map_df$Country_Area == 'Brunei Darussalam'] <- 'Brunei'
map_df$Country_Area[map_df$Country_Area == 'United States'] <- 'USA'
map_df$Country_Area[map_df$Country_Area == 'Trinidad and Tobago'] <- 'Trinidad'
map_df$Country_Area[map_df$Country_Area == 'Syrian Arab Republic'] <- 'Syria'
map_df[map_df$Country_Area=='China',2:8] <- map_df[map_df$Country_Area=='China',2:8] + map_df[map_df$Country_Area=='Hong Kong',2:8]
map_df <- map_df %>%
  filter(Country_Area != 'Hong Kong')

#data merge & manipulation
energy_map <- merge(mapdata, map_df, by.x = 'region', by.y = 'Country_Area')
energy_map <- arrange(energy_map, group, order)
energy_map$Energy_Supply_per_capita <- log10(energy_map$Energy_Supply_per_capita)

#plot the map + fill color + clean theme
q <- ggplot(energy_map, aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group, fill=Energy_Supply_per_capita)) +
  geom_polygon(colour="black", size = 0.75)
q <- q + scale_fill_gradient2(name = 'Energy Supply\nper capita(log)',breaks = c(2.5,2,1.5,1),labels = c(300,100,30,10),low="blue", mid="yellow2", high="red",
                                                      midpoint = quantile(energy_map$Energy_Supply_per_capita,0.26))
q <- q + theme_clean() + theme(legend.text=element_text(size=15), legend.title=element_text(size=15))
q
